title: For Sale/Trade:  Star modelo super b
postcontent:
This particular handgun was a commercial export to the US in 9mm luger, so regular old 9mm.  It is in very good condition and fires without any hiccups.  Comes with one mag and holster.  9mm ammo available for reasonable prices with purchase.

The whole family of the "Star" pistol was (and stil is) manufactured by the Spain-based company Bonifacio Echeverria, SA. Back in the 1920s the company began to develop semi-automatic pistols, based on Browning-designed Colt M1911 design. These pistols were more or less similar to the original M1911, but usually chambered for 9x19mm Luger or 9x23mm Largo (Bergmann-Bayard) rounds.
The Star mod. A was chambered for 9mm Largo ammunition and mostly used in the Spain. The mod. B was chambered for 9x19mm Luger and had been widely exported into many countries, including Hitlers' Germany, and had been used during World War 2. The Star model P had been chambered for .45ACP cartridge and mostly intended for American market. The model BM was a compact version of the mod. B with shorter barrel and slide.
The Model B Super replaced the Mod. B in the production and in the Spain Army arsenals, and had been in production in 1946 - 1965, and had been in use by Spanish military until early 1990s, when new Star M30 had been adopted as a new service sidearm.
The Star pistols, mod. A, B and P were similar in design and differed mostly in caliber. All these pistols were recoil operated, locked breech, single action pistols that used Browning-deigned, linked barrel locking principle. The models A Super and B Super differed from mod. A and B, respectively, only in that the Super model utilised linkless locking scheme, similar to that used in Browning High Power pistols.
Being very similar in appearance to the Colt m1911A1 pistols, the Star pistols had some differences.
First, these pistols had no automated grip safety, and no detachable backstrap/mainspring housing
Second, Star pistols had simplified trigger/sear design with single trigger link, and pivoting trigger
Third, external safety swiths locked the hammer, not the sear
Fourth, Star pistols featured exetrnal extractors
Fifth, as noted above, Star A Super and B Super also had different barrel locking/unlocking
In general, all these pistols were of high quality, and offered good performance

title: For Sale/Trade:  Browning BDM
postcontent: 9mm luger Browning BDM. this gun is in excellent shape. it is in the factory hard case and unlike most handguns of the Clinton era it has two 15 round factory mag with it instead of the 10 round mags that most guns in the Clinton era were limited to. these mags are almost impossible to find and are worth a lot of money. ebay sells the 10 round mags for 35 to 50 bucks making the 15 round mags worth a lot more. the BDM is a unique gun (BDM stands for "Browning Double Mode") it has a switch on the side that can be set for "P" or pistol mode and the gun acts like a modern day double/single action pistol or "R" for Revolver mode and the gun acts like a modern day single action revolver. the gun has a decocking safety and looks almost exactly like a browning high power. the gun shoots very accurately and is very slim and light weight. it has a 4.75" barrel with adjustable sights.  I am looking to trade for a beretta px4 storm in 9mm. this BDM is the only gun I was willing to get rid of to get the rotating barrel of the storm. otherwise I am going to sell it out rite and use the cash to purchase one. you wont be disappointed with this gun!! it is an excellent shooting firearm. I will upload pictures later today.

title: For Sale/Trade:  2000 Jeep Cherokee
postcontent:
2000 Jeep Cherokee Sport 

Second owner. Have title. Make me an offer!

The Good:
- Newer Transfer Case (never been engaged with drive shaft)
- A/C works
- Alternator is only a week old
- Starter has been replaced in the last 9000 miles
- Flex plate and torque converter are newer
- Power Steering pump, water pump, thermostat, A/C converter all recently replaced
- Newer Duralast battery
- New Tires (less than 10K miles)
- Starts and runs
- Lights (interior and exterior), Power Windows, and Power door locks are all working
- Auto Transmission with no issues
- Replaced rusted brake lines

The Bad:
- No four wheel drive shaft (Bent when original transfer case blew)
- Dent in hood (Hood latch has been replaced)
- Exhaust has been cut in the past, but is functional.
- Interior is decent, but headliner had exploding dr. pepper hit it.

Took it to Coughlin in Marysville in 2010, asked them to take a look at the torque converter, and they told me it needed a crank bearing. Turns out, it wasn't the engine at all, it was the flex plate and torque converter that needed replaced. Pulled the engine for no reason in spring of 2010. Needless to say, I was upset when I found the issue on the flex plate, and they refunded me my $188.

Engine has been pulled and has a rattle from a cut star headed bolt. Used the cut bolt as a guide when putting the engine back in, but now it rattles in it's hole. Rear drums need replaced, but internal shoes and master cylinders were replaced in 2010, and it's only had about 15K miles since then. Just replaced rusted brake lines on Saturday.

I don't know which transmission it has. Its never been replaced, no issues, and its an automatic. The 4WD can be engaged, don't know what the front differential is like. Might need flushed before setting up 4WD. I had ATS in Marysville replace the transfer case in 2008, and I've never replaced the 4 wheel drive shaft. Haven't needed the 4WD shaft, but transfer case does engage properly.

Need $1200 to cover parts and tires. Good fixer upper for someone who knows what they're doing.

Engine runs strong. I have a nice truck and don't have time to work on it anymore. I'm selling it because I don't have the time to work on it, and I need to pay off some credit card debt.
